&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What this demonstrates:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;code&gt;constructor&lt;/code&gt; sets initial state&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;code&gt;componentDidMount&lt;/code&gt; fetches data on first render&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;code&gt;componentDidUpdate&lt;/code&gt; handles prop changes intelligently&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;code&gt;componentWillUnmount&lt;/code&gt; prevents memory leaks&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;code&gt;render&lt;/code&gt; stays pure and simple&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;




&lt;h2&gt;


Key Takeaways
&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Understanding class component lifecycle methods gives you:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;‚úÖ &lt;strong&gt;Better debugging skills&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì You'll know exactly when and why components re-render&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
‚úÖ &lt;strong&gt;Deeper React mental model&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Hooks aren't magic, they're lifecycle methods in disguise&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
‚úÖ &lt;strong&gt;Legacy codebase confidence&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì Many production apps still use class components&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
‚úÖ &lt;strong&gt;Performance optimization knowledge&lt;/strong&gt; ‚Äì You'll understand when to use &lt;code&gt;memo&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;useMemo&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;useCallback&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hooks didn't replace lifecycle concepts‚Äîthey just changed the API. The underlying principles remain the same.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Whether you're maintaining legacy code or just want to truly understand React, mastering lifecycle methods is time well spent.&lt;/p&gt;




